==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lich
<hw>Lich</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧ch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>l⟦imac⟧c</ets> body. See <er>Like</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>A
dead body; a corpse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Lich fowl</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the European
goatsucker; -- called also <altname>lich owl</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>Lich gate</b></col>, <cd>a covered gate through which the corpse
was carried to the church or burial place, and where the bier was placed
to await the clergyman; a corpse gate.</cd> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<au>Halliwell.</au> -- <col><b>Lich wake</b></col>, <cd>the wake, or
watching, held over a corpse before burial.</cd> <mark>[Prov
Eng.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>Lich wall</b></col>, <cd>the
wall of a churchyard or burying ground.</cd> -- <col><b>Lich
way</b></col>, <cd>the path by which the dead are carried to the
grave.</cd> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lichanura</ent>⟦br⟧
